description.value:
Limestone corner fragment, possibly a plinth or an offering table, inscribed with the cartouche of Akhenaten.

On top of the fragment is a circular shallow recess and partial remains of another recess with a straight edge. The front edge is smoothed, while the left side contains a partial horizontal line of incised text. The remaining two sides are heavily damaged with no surviving inscription, and the corners of the stone are also chipped. On the base of the fragment, ‘Tell Amarna’ is written in red ink.

description.value:
Fragmentary greywacke rounded base for a statue, only the front section now remaining.

Across the top of the base is a right-side corner of stone that may have formed part of a naos shrine or stela, which is now lost. Across the front of this corner are partial incised signs of text, further suggesting that it provided a flat surface across the front. Along the top of the base are three rows of incised text reading from right to left. The beginning of each line is now damaged, and the final sign of the third line is also damaged. Around the side of the base is a single horizontal line of incised text that reads continuously from the left side around to the right side. This likely concluded on the reverse of the base, which is now broken.

The surface is worn around the sides of the base, obscuring some of the hieroglyph signs particularly from the left side and moving to the front. There are also small chips to the top rounded edge of the base.

description.value: Round bottomed bowl, sheet brass engraved and inlaid with silver, gold and black organic inlay. Around the outside of the bowl is an inscrption frieze interrupted by six roundels containing flying birds arranged symmetrically around an 8-petalled whirling rosette. Below this frieze is a narrow arabesque scroll border interrupted by six 6 petalled whirling rosettes. The base is decorated with a large roundel containing a design based on six intersecting circles. The interstices contain either four flying birds on interlace or plain interlace with a central multi-petalled whirling rosette. Around this is a wide band divided by slightly wavy interlace, plain interlace, groups of three vines or lotus. The interior base of the bowl is covered with a design of swimming fish and balls around a central multi-petalled whirling rosette. Despite the use of a compass, it is iregularly laid out.

description.value: Extremely wide and shallow axe-head: possessing at the top end of the butt an additional hafting-device in the form of a small perforated protuberance. The upper tip is rounded, the lower tapers to form a lug, the end of which is broken. There are eight binding-holes, in addition to the small hole at the top, which was intended to take a rivet for the fixing of a metal cap or ferrule. Several of the larger holes bear the remains of the original binding. The blade is of rather rough work. It is warped and has an uneven butt and cutting end. It is thickly corroded and remains of the original wooden haft are preserved. A small crack runs between the central perforation and the butt. The cutting edge is mostly obscured by corrosion product. It appears originally to have been thin but not very sharp.

description.value: Bronze battle-axe-head: the three binding holes are well spaced and aligned and are relatively small. Two cylindrical ferrules are corroded, in their original position, on to the ends of the butt. The capped, upper ferrule is split down the rear and at the top, and the lower ferrule is similarly damaged just beyond the lug. Both the axe and the ferrules are thickly corroded. The ferrules bear the clear impression of the original binding, the width of these marks indicating that the thong in each case was wound around the ferrule several times, and the line of the haft is preserved along the butt of the axe. Unusually, the butt appears to have been slightly bevelled.

description.value: Finely fashioned bronze axe-head: with almost evenly concave sides forming a relatively narrow waist mid-way between the butt and the cutting end. It has thin angular lugs and a convex cutting edge with pointed corners. The butt is inclined, giving the blade an asymmetrical shape, with one side (the upper when the blade was hafted) being longer than the other. The sides are faceted. Once covered by a rich patination, the blade has been cleaned since its acquisition. There is superficial pitting all over, most severely on the lugs. The cutting edge is frayed. Both faces bear the same lightly chased hieroglyphic inscription. Part of the prenomen on one face has been obliterated by corrosion damage, which has also, less severely, affected the other cartouches.

description.value: Large crescentic axe-head: with 11 rivet-holes, three in the central tang, four in each of the lateral tangs. The upper tip of the blade is missing. The cutting edge has been damaged by corrosion in parts but bears no clear signs of wear. There is superficial damage on both faces. The blade is attached to a tubular casing, made of silver, which probably once enclosed a wooden haft, now disappeared. The tubing contains several cracks and holes and its upper part is lost, revealing the metal rivets. Since its acquisition, the casing has been reinforced. None of the rivets are complete. Some are missing, others have suffered corrosion damage. All were once capped with silver studs, only one of which now survives intact. At the bottom the casing contains a small aperture of uncertain purpose.

description.value: Arsenical copper battle-axe-head: with original wooden haft and metal ferrule. The blade is thin and there are four binding-holes, which are misaligned.  The lugs are hooked. The axe has been cleaned of corrosion product and is in good condition, though there are small  surface  imperfections.  The  cutting  edge, though thinner than is normal for this type, is not very sharp. It is very slightly indented in parts, possibly as a result of use.
